1 and
2 (B) Under average annual operating conditions, has a nominal electric generating capacity:
3 (i) Of less than 50 megawatts and the fuel chargeable to power heat rate value is not greater
4 than 6,000 Btu per kilowatt hour;
5 (ii) Of 50 megawatts or more and the fuel chargeable to power heat rate value is not greater
6 than 5,500 Btu per kilowatt hour; or
7 (iii) Specified by the Energy Facility Siting Council by rule based on the council’s determination
8 relating to emissions of the energy facility.
9 (d) Temporary storage, at the site of a nuclear-fueled thermal power plant for which a site cer-
10 tificate has been issued by the State of Oregon, of radioactive waste from the plant.
11 (e) An energy facility as defined in ORS 469.300 (12)(a)(G), if the plant also produces a secondary
12 fuel used on site for the production of heat or electricity, if the output of the primary fuel is less
13 than six billion Btu of heat a day.
14 (f) An energy facility as defined in ORS 469.300 (12)(a)(G), if the facility:
15 (A) Exclusively uses biomass, including but not limited to grain, whey, potatoes, oilseeds, waste
16 vegetable oil or cellulosic biomass, as the source of material for conversion to a liquid fuel;
17 (B) Has received local land use approval under the applicable acknowledged comprehensive plan
18 and land use regulations of the affected local government and the facility complies with any state-
19 wide planning goals or rules of the Land Conservation and Development Commission that are di-
20 rectly applicable to the facility;
21 (C) Requires no new electric transmission lines or gas or petroleum product pipelines that would
22 require a site certificate under subsection (1) of this section;
23 (D) Produces synthetic fuel, at least 90 percent of which is used in an industrial or refueling
24 facility located within one mile of the facility or is transported from the facility by rail or barge;
25 and
26 (E) Emits less than 118 pounds of carbon dioxide per million Btu from fossil fuel used for con-
27 version energy.
28 (g) A standby generation facility, if the facility complies with all of the following:
29 (A) The facility has received local land use approval under the applicable acknowledged com-
30 prehensive plan and land use regulations of the affected local government and the facility complies
31 with all statewide planning goals and applicable rules of the Land Conservation and Development
32 Commission;
33 (B) The standby generators have been approved by the Department of Environmental Quality
34 as having complied with all applicable air and water quality requirements. For an applicant that
35 proposes to provide the physical facilities for the installation of standby generators, the requirement
36 of this subparagraph may be met by agreeing to require such a term in the lease contract for the
37 facility; and
38 (C) The standby generators are:
39 (i) Electrically incapable of being interconnected to the transmission grid. For an applicant that
40 proposes to provide the physical facilities for the installation of standby generators under this sub-
41 subparagraph, the requirement of this sub-subparagraph may be met by agreeing to require such a
42 term in the lease contract for the facility; or
43 (ii) Electrically capable of being interconnected to the grid but are dispatched to the grid by a
44 local transmission and distribution grid operator or balancing authority to support grid reliability,
45 are operated consistent with 40 C.F.R. 63.6640(f), as in effect on March 27, 2024, and are exclusively
[2]

A-Eng. HB 4031
1 using renewable fuels, including renewable diesel, renewable natural gas or renewable hydrogen, if
2 such fuels are available and if their use does not violate the warranty or certification of the gen-
3 erator.
4 (h) An energy facility if:
5 (A) The facility produces power exclusively from one or more of the following:
6 (i) Solar photovoltaic or thermal energy;
7 (ii) Wind energy;
8 (iii) Geothermal energy; or
9 (iv) Marine energy;
10 (B) The developer of the facility:
11 (i) Submits, on or before December 31, 2028, a land use application to construct or oper-
12 ate the facility to, and receives approval from, the local government within whose jurisdic-
13 tion the facility is proposed to be located; and
14 (ii) Provides a written or electronic notification to the local government, and a copy of
15 the notification to the Energy Facility Siting Council, that:
16 (I) Confirms that construction of the facility has begun such that the facility qualifies
17 for a tax credit authorized under section 45, 45Y, 48 or 48E of the Internal Revenue Code;
18 (II) Identifies the applicant and facility;
19 (III) Identifies the applicable federal tax credits; and
20 (IV) Includes a brief description of actions taken to begin construction, within the
21 meaning of the applicable notices, regulations or rulings of the United States Department
22 of the Treasury or Internal Revenue Service; and
23 (C) The facility is placed in service:
24 (i) On or before December 31, 2030; or
25 (ii) If the facility is placed in service after December 31, 2030, on or before a date allowed
26 by exception by the United States Department of the Treasury or Internal Revenue Service
27 by which date the facility still qualifies for a tax credit under section 45, 45Y, 48 or 48E of
28 the Internal Revenue Code.
29 (3) The Energy Facility Siting Council may review and, if necessary, revise the fuel chargeable
30 to power heat rate value set forth in subsection (2)(c)(B) of this section. In making its determination,
31 the council shall ensure that the fuel chargeable to power heat rate value for facilities set forth in
32 subsection (2)(c)(B) of this section remains significantly lower than the fuel chargeable to power
33 heat rate value for the best available, commercially viable thermal power plant technology at the
34 time of the revision.
35 (4)(a)(A) Any person who proposes to construct or enlarge an energy facility and who claims an
36 exemption under subsection (2)(a), (c) or (f) of this section from the requirement to obtain a site
37 certificate shall request the Energy Facility Siting Council to determine whether the proposed fa-
38 cility qualifies for the claimed exemption.
39 (B) The council may not require a person who operates or proposes to construct or enlarge an
40 energy facility to request that the council determine whether the proposed facility qualifies for ex-
41 emption under subsection (2)(g) of this section.
42 (b) The council shall make its determination within 60 days after the request for exemption is
43 filed. An appeal from the council’s determination on a request for exemption shall be made under
44 ORS 469.403, except that the scope of review by the Supreme Court shall be the same as a review
45 by a circuit court under ORS 183.484. The record on review by the Supreme Court shall be the re-
[3]

A-Eng. HB 4031
1 cord established in the council proceeding on the exemption.
2 (5) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, a separate site certificate shall not be re-
3 quired for:
4 (a) Transmission lines, battery energy storage systems, storage facilities, pipelines or similar
5 related or supporting facilities, if such related or supporting facilities are addressed in and are
6 subject to a site certificate for another energy facility;
7 (b) Expansion within the site or within the energy generation area of a facility for which a site
8 certificate has been issued, if the existing site certificate has been amended to authorize expansion;
9 or
10 (c) Expansion, either within the site or outside the site, of an existing council certified surface
11 facility related to an underground gas storage reservoir, if the existing site certificate is amended
12 to authorize expansion.
13 (6) If the substantial loss of the steam host causes a facility exempt under subsection (2)(c) of
14 this section to substantially fail to meet the exemption requirements under subsection (2)(c) of this
15 section, the electric generating facility shall cease to operate one year after the substantial loss of
16 the steam host unless an application for a site certificate has been filed in accordance with the
17 provisions of ORS 469.300 to 469.563.
18 (7) As used in this section:
19 (a) “Standby generation facility” means an electric power generating facility, including standby
20 generators and the physical structures necessary to install and connect standby generators, that
21 provides temporary electric power:
22 (A) In the event of a power outage and that is electrically incapable of being interconnected
23 with the transmission grid; or
24 (B) Consistent with 40 C.F.R. 63.6640(f), as in effect on March 27, 2024.
25 (b) “Total energy output” means the sum of useful thermal energy output and useful electrical
26 energy output.
27 (c) “Useful thermal energy” means the verifiable thermal energy used in any viable industrial
28 or commercial process, heating or cooling application.
29 (8)(a) If the developer of a facility elects, or the governing body of the local government after
30 consulting with the developer elects, to defer regulatory authority to the Energy Facility Siting
31 Council, the developer of a facility shall obtain a site certificate, in the manner provided in ORS
32 469.300 to 469.563, 469.590 to 469.619, 469.930 and 469.992, for a facility that, notwithstanding the
33 definition of “energy facility” in ORS 469.300, is:
34 (A) An electric power generating plant with an average electric generating capacity of less than
35 100 megawatts produced from wind energy at a single energy facility or within a single energy
36 generation area;
37 (B) An associated transmission line;
38 (C) A battery energy storage system; or
39 (D) A solar photovoltaic power generation facility that is not an energy facility as defined in
40 ORS 469.300 (12)(a)(D).
41 (b) An election by a developer or a local government under this subsection is final.
42 (c) An election by a local government under this subsection is not a land use decision as defined
43 in ORS 197.015.
44 (d) A local government may not make an election under this subsection after a permit applica-
45 tion has been submitted under ORS 215.416 or 227.175.
